II. 1 The mere Law of Nations, setting aside the consideration of other duties, of which we shall afterwards speak, does not except sacred edifices, that is, those which are dedicated to God orto gods. When places are taken by the enemy, all ceases to be sacred, as Pompo- nius the Jurist says. The sacred places of Syracuse were desecrated by victory, as Cicero says. The cause of this is that the places which are called sacred are not really abstracted from human uses 3 but are called sacred in consideration of the end to which they are destined.
